
[1]shame

   SHAME, n.

   1. A painful sensation excited by a consciousness of guilt, or of
   having done something which injures reputation; or by of that which
   nature nature or modesty prompts us to conceal. Shame is particularly
   excited by the disclosure of actions which, in the view of men, are
   mean and degrading. Hence it it is often or always manifested by a
   downcast look or by blushes, called confusion of face.

   Hide, for shame,

   Romans, your grandsires' images,

   That blush at their degenerate progeny. Dryden.
